	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>South Centre analysis issues faced in central African EPA negotiations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 September 2007
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> A recent South Centre analytical note highlights a number of key elements as background to the negotiations, notably:</p>
<ul>

<li> the weak level of economic integration amongst the countries of the Central African EPA configuration, with decisions ‘either only partially implemented or not applied’;</li>

<li> the limited effectiveness of the Central Africa regional preparatory task force;</li>

<li> the failure to fully conclude phase-2 negotiations before launching the ‘3rd and final phase of negotiations;</li>

<li> uncertainty at the technical level over the ability to conclude the negotiations before the end of the year;</li>

<li> the heavy dependence on the EU as a source of imports and the heavy concentration on food and agricultural imports (wheat, wheat flour, malt, semolina preparations, soya oil, canned tomatoes, chicken, and dairy products).</li>

</ul>
<p>
 <br/> </p><p> It notes the extensive import of food and agricultural products from the EU despite the heavy reliance of the region on agriculture for employment and incomes for the rural population. The high dependence on the EU market for agricultural exports is also highlighted.</p><p> Key issues faced in the EPA negotiations highlighted in the South Centre report include:</p>
<ul>

<li> making the link between the development dimension and regional integration, with development support seen as essential by central African negotiators, while the EC is reluctant to include it formally in the EPA (although there are now discussions on an EPA regional fund, which would provide a vehicle for facilitating access to existing aid instruments);</li>

<li> market-access commitments notably how to deal with sensitive products in the construction of the central Africa tariff offer to the EU (most notably for agricultural and food products);</li>

<li> agricultural market access, preference erosion and accompanying measures issues, with considerable importance being attached to ‘levelling up of central African productive agricultural capacity’;</li>

</ul>
<p> The South Centre analysis notes that under an EPA ‘the entire CEMAC+ region would be expected to reduce and eliminate agricultural applied tariffs’, with only a limited number of tariff lines being treated separately ‘by virtue of their sensitiveness’. The South Centre cites analysis which suggests an EPA will increase central African imports of food and agricultural products from the EU and ‘reduce domestic production of agro-processed products’. The analysis notes that ‘although the EPA text proposed by the EU recognises the social and economic importance of agriculture and the food security and livelihood security needs of the region, it negates the importance of tariffs as an instrument to promote this sector’.</p><p> The note suggests consideration be given to protecting local products that would be put in direct competition with products receiving subsidies from the EU, particularly where there is scope for expanding intra-regional trade (beef, paddy rice, cocoa and sugar). Special safeguard measures to protect against import surges are also called for, particularly since Congo DRC, Gabon, and Central African Republic have suffered such import surges in recent years.</p><p> The text notes that the EC includes no provisions to deal with the impact of EU agricultural subsidies, despite the fact that these policies could threaten the livelihoods of central African producers in areas such as dairy products, sugar, chicken, vegetable oil and wheat flour.</p><p> The paper concludes by calling for more time for negotiations to secure a pro-development outcome and consideration of alternative trade arrangements ‘in case the scheduled deadlines cannot be met without compromising the development promise of the EPAs’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> South Centre (SC/AN/TDP/EPA/9-June 2007)</p><p>

<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/South Centre_EN_010607_South Centre_EPA-negotiations-in-the-Central-African-region-some-issues-for-consideration.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/South%20Centre_EN_010607_South...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Trends in EU food and agricultural exports to CEMAC have been variable since 2000, with the value of exports of live animals and meat products and oils, fats and waxes falling (by 13% and 56.1% respectively) and the value of exports of vegetable products and prepared food and drink products increasing (by 16.5% and 21.6% respectively). Prepared food and drinks in 2005 accounted for 51.06% of all food and agricultural exports to the CEMAC region, compared to 45% in 2000. Overall over the period the value of EU food-and-agricultural product exports to the CEMAC region rose by 6.4% compared to a 7.8% increase in the value of total EU exports to the CEMAC region. The three-year annual average share of EU food-and-agricultural exports to total EU exports to the CEMAC region increased from 14.77% in 2000-2002 to 15.47% in 2003-2005.</p><p> There would therefore appear to be a basis for concerns about the future impact of an EPA and agricultural value chains in the CEMAC region.</p><p><b>EU food and agricultural exports by broad classification to CEMAC region</b> </p><table class="renderedtable" border="medium none" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
